<article>
    <h1>STAY&#xAD;ING THERE</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200830/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-30"><time>2020-08-30</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE TRAVEL</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Old-world charm</p>
    <p>Nes­tled in Russell, a quaint town that was New Zealand’s first sea­port, is The Duke Of Marl­bor­ough Ho­tel on the wa­ter­front.</p>
    <p>Lov­ingly re­stored, the ho­tel started op­er­at­ing in 1827 and be­came the coun­try’s first li­censed ho­tel in 1840. It is a com­fort­able stay at the 38-room, dou­ble-storey ho­tel, com­plete with mod­ern ameni­ties and qual­ity tea bags.</p>
    <p>The restau­rant is a des­ti­na­tion in it­self. Savour fresh lo­cal Waikare in­let oys­ters with a glass of Sauvi­gnon blanc while watch­ing the sun set over the wa­ter from the bal­cony. Go to www.the­duke.co.nz</p>
    <p>Chic city liv­ing</p>
    <p>Over­look­ing the vi­brant Princes</p>
    <p>Wharf, the con­tem­po­rary M So­cial Auck­land Ho­tel has 190 chic rooms across 12 floors.</p>
    <p>My suite has a har­bour view and a plush bed. So­fas to sink into await din­ers at the on-site Beast and But­ter­flies restau­rant, where break­fast is served in a wel­com­ing space with floor-to-ceil­ing win­dows.</p>
    <p>The friendly staff seem gen­uinely en­thused about mak­ing the stay pleas­ant for guests.</p>
    <p>The carpark is ac­ces­si­ble only to staff, so just drive to the en­trance, and your car will be parked for you.</p>
    <p>In the evening, take a short drive to Or­phan’s Kitchen, a mod­ern 40-seat restau­rant on Pon­sonby Road that is into sus­tain­able eat­ing.</p>
    <p>When I was there, the menu in­cluded sprouted quinoa cro­quettes with sesame mayo and romesco, wild veni­son carpac­cio with tamar­illo and oys­ters with chardon­nay granita.</p>
    <p>Or opt for line-caught fish with as­para­gus and snap­per-head bor­de­laise, wood roast half chook with kim­chi and other con­tem­po­rary New Zealand fare.</p>
    <p>The ho­tel is closed till Nov 1. Go to str.sg/J7eL and www.or­phan­skitchen.co.nz.</p>


